\subsection{Maximum Likelihood method}
\label{sec:ML}

We  here present the methodology of determining the SARDF and the HGMF simultaneously as a bivariate distribution function of stellar mass and specific accretion rate, i.e. $\Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z)$, where $\Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z) {\mathrm{d}} \log M_\star {\mathrm{d}} \log {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}$ gives the space density of AGN with stellar mass host galaxies between $\log M_\star$ and $\log M_\star+{\mathrm{d}}\log M_\star$ and a specific accretion rate between $\log {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}$ and $\log {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}+{\mathrm{d}}\log {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}$ at the redshift $z$. The HGMF, SARDF and the X-ray AGN LF (XLF) can be derived as different marginalizations over this bivariate distribution function.
We use the maximum likelihood method developed by \citet{Schulze2010} and extended by \citet{Schulze2015} to compute $\Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z)$. While these works focused on the joint determination of the active black hole mass function and the Eddington ratio distribution function (using type 1 AGN), the method is implemented here for the joint determination of the HGMF and SARDF.

The technique minimizes the likelihood function $S=-2 \sum \ln p_i$, where the probability distribution $p_i$ for each object is given by:
\begin{eqnarray}
p_i(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},N_H,z)  & = & \frac{1}{N} \Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z)\, \mathcal{I}\left (M_\star, {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}, z, N_H\right ) \,  \nonumber\\ 
     & &        \times f\left (N_H\mid L_X, z\right ) \frac{{\mathrm{d}} V}{{\mathrm{d}} z}  \ ,
 \label{eq:pi}
\end{eqnarray}

where $\Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z)$ is the bivariate distribution function of stellar mass and specific accretion rate that we want to derive, $\mathcal{I}\left (M_\star, {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}, z, N_H\right ) = \mathcal{I}(L_X,z,N_H)$ is the X-ray selection function given by the sensitivity map in the 2-10 keV band and $f\left (N_H\mid L_X, z\right )$ is the absorption distribution function, taken from \citet{Ueda2014}. We use the $N_H$ estimates presented in Sec.~\ref{sec:sar} to compute $L_X$ (and therefore {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}) and $f\left (N_H\mid L_X, z\right )$ for our sample.
The factor $N$ corresponds to the total number of objects in the sample predicted by the model and it is given by integrating over $M_\star$, {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}\ , N$_{\rm H}$, and $z$, i.e.
\begin{eqnarray}
&N = \iiiint \Psi(M_\star,{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}},z)\, \mathcal{I}\left (M_\star, {\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}}, z, N_H\right ) \,  \nonumber\\ 
      &         \times f\left (N_H\mid L_X, z\right ) \frac{{\mathrm{d}} V}{{\mathrm{d}} z}  \rm{dlog} N_H \rm{dlog}{\ensuremath{\mathcal{\lambda_{\rm SAR}}}} \rm{dlog}M_\star \rm{d}z\ ,
 \label{eq:pi2}
\end{eqnarray}

\noindent
